Text: Historical particularism, coined by Marvin Harris in the 1960s, is widely considered the first American anthropological school of thought. Founded by Franz Boas, it rejected the cultural evolutionary model that dominated anthropology until Boas' time. Each society is a collective representation of its unique historical past, according to historical particularism. Boas also rejected parallel evolutionism, which suggests all societies follow the same path and reach their level of development in the same way. Instead, historical particularism showed that societies can achieve similar cultural development through different means. Boas suggested that diffusion, trade, environment, and historical accident can create similar cultural traits. He identified three factors to explain cultural customs: environmental conditions, psychological factors, and historical connections, with history being the most important. Critics argue that historical particularism is antitheoretical because it doesn't seek universal theories applicable to all cultures. Boas believed that theories would emerge from collected data. This school of thought was uniquely American and Boas, arguably, the most influential anthropological thinker in American history.
